    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2021-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2021-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1)	HRC supported in the development of a strategic plan
2)	Promoting Human Rights Project revised and validated</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1) Strengthened the strategic capacity of the human rights commission. With UNDP support, the institution prepared the following documents: a)	Draft five-year strategic plan, and b) Final five-year strategic plan, c)	Implementation Plan.

2) With UNDP support, key actors and stakeholders working on Human Rights developed a concept note taking into consideration the emerging issues and new priorities of the new administration.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2019-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2019-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">Raise awareness among stakeholders, especially Zambia Police Service, on the contributions of Formed Police Units to the promotion an strengthening of human rights at national and international level.

Conduct stakeholder engagement on the developed NMRF and define their roles in monitoring state party reporting. 

Engage civil society organisations in state reporting and strengthen their understanding of the NMRF. 

Raise awareness on human rights issues in Zambia mong rights holders/the public. Support preparations of the International Human Rights Day 2019.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">The Ministry of Justice, with UNDP financial and technical support and partnership with the OHCHR, Regional Office for Southern Africa, supported the capacity development of 25 Civil Society Organizations (representative of women, children, person with disabilities, albinism, sexual minorities, extractive industries, prisoners, land issues, media) for them to effectively engage with human rights reporting mechanisms. These UN human rights mechanisms include treaty bodies, UPR and Special Procedure Mandate Holders). The CSOs have formed a networking platform that will enable them better engage and defend human rights in Zambia.

&#xF0A7;	Zambia is signatory to several treaties and conventions thereby committing to international norms and standards aiming at improving human security, access to justice and equal opportunity under the law. As a result of limited coordination efforts in preparing the national reports required under the international obligations, Zambia has a backlog of overdue reports. UNDP supported the Ministry of Justice to establish a National Mechanism for Implementation, Reporting and Follow up (NMRF) comprising of 7-line Ministries, the Human Rights Commission and 3 Civil Society Organisations.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2020-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2020-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">With the outbreak of COVID-19, resources were reprogrammed with the following targets:
4.1: Number of developed gender sensitive Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) for maintaining law enforcement during COVID-19 by Zambia Police Service (ZPS)
Baseline: 0, Target: 1
4.2: Number of police officers trained as master trainers on COVID-19 response by Zambia Police Baseline: 0, Target: 30 including 15 women officers 4.3: Number of police officers provided with actionable information on maintaining international human rights standards and preventing COVID-19 Baseline: 0, Target: 2,100 including at least 50% of women
4.4: Number of of information products distributed to police officers on Law enforcement and COVID-19.
Baseline: 0 Target: 3,000</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project leveraged UN local and international resources from Ministry of Justice, Human Rights Commission UN Police, and the Office of the High Commissioner on Human Rights to support the response efforts of the Zambia Police Service. 

Financial and technical resources enabled the Zambia Police Service to develop comprehensive Standard Operating Procedures to guide law enforcement response to COVID-19. Through virtual training, the UN enhanced the skills of police officers in international policing and human rights standards as well as general information about COVID-19. 

Support enabled the development of training guidelines and tools for the master trainers. The Zambia Police Service Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) Against COVID-19 include strong human rights and gender dimensions and provide for various scenarios depending on the gravity of the COVID-19 cases and prevention measures announced by government. 

The SOPs will enable the Zambia Police Service which includes over 22,000 officers to act appropriately in enforcing COVID-19 measures.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
